===Etymology===
'''GI''' was originally an initialism for ''Galvanized Iron''; during the 1930s the usage expanded to stand for ''Government Issue''; by World War II it had become a nickname for the soldiers themselves.
, later for  and applied to all articles issued in conformity with US military regulations or procedures.

a US Army clerks' term for items such as ''G.I. cans:'' trash cans that are galvanized.  ''G.I. cans'' was also used to refer sardonically to shells fired by the [[w:German Army|German Army]] in [[w:WWI|WWI]].

